{
"id":"mk19_bb_en_s15",
"subspecialtyId":"en",
"title":"Hypoadrenalism",
"jsonContent":{
"type":"section",
"id":"mk19_bb_en_s15",
"title":{
"__html":"Hypoadrenalism"
},
"titleNode":{
"type":"section-title",
"hlId":"5ba607",
"children":[
"Hypoadrenalism"
]
},
"children":[
{
"type":"section",
"id":"mk19_bb_en_s15_1",
"title":{
"__html":"Diagnosis"
},
"titleNode":{
"type":"section-title",
"hlId":"523223",
"children":[
"Diagnosis"
]
},
"children":[
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"a18cc9",
"children":[
"Adrenal insufficiency may be caused by disease of the adrenal glands (primary) or disorders of the pituitary gland (secondary). Primary disease (Addison disease) results in loss of cortisol, aldosterone, and adrenal androgens; secondary insufficiency causes only cortisol and adrenal androgen deficiencies (aldosterone synthesis is not ",
{
"type":"abbreviation",
"title":"adrenocorticotropic hormone",
"children":[
"ACTH"
]
},
" dependent)."
]
},
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"703286",
"children":[
" ",
{
"type":"tag",
"tagName":"b",
"attrs":{
},
"children":[
"Symptoms and Signs"
]
},
" "
]
},
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"22910c",
"children":[
"Characteristic findings include:"
]
},
{
"type":"list",
"children":[
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"e4a22a",
"children":[
"weight loss"
]
},
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"f98c78",
"children":[
"fatigue, anorexia, nausea, vomiting, abdominal pain"
]
},
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"17b312",
"children":[
"orthostatic hypotension"
]
},
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"ee34a9",
"children":[
"hypoglycemia"
]
},
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"210c55",
"children":[
"eosinophilia"
]
},
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"94fc85",
"children":[
"hyperpigmentation (primary adrenal insufficiency only)"
]
},
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"89d198",
"children":[
"hyponatremia and hyperkalemia (primary adrenal insufficiency only)"
]
},
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"d715d3",
"children":[
"hypercalcemia"
]
},
" "
]
},
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"182bf7",
"children":[
" ",
{
"type":"tag",
"tagName":"b",
"attrs":{
},
"children":[
"Causes"
]
},
" "
]
},
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"304c70",
"children":[
{
"type":"tag",
"tagName":"b",
"attrs":{
},
"children":[
"Autoimmune adrenalitis"
]
},
" is the most common cause of primary insufficiency."
]
},
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"91da65",
"children":[
{
"type":"tag",
"tagName":"b",
"attrs":{
},
"children":[
"Glucocorticoid use"
]
},
" is the most common cause of secondary insufficiency (hypothalamic-pituitary suppression). Look for patients who recently discontinued glucocorticoid therapy or did not increase their glucocorticoid dose in times of stress."
]
}
]
},
{
"type":"section",
"id":"mk19_bb_en_s15_2",
"title":{
"__html":"Testing"
},
"titleNode":{
"type":"section-title",
"hlId":"fa6a5a",
"children":[
"Testing"
]
},
"children":[
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"68c22a",
"children":[
"An 8:00 ",
{
"type":"tag",
"tagName":"small",
"attrs":{
},
"children":[
"AM"
]
},
" serum cortisol <3 μg/dL confirms cortisol deficiency and values >18 μg/dL exclude the diagnosis."
]
},
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"0f07df",
"children":[
"For patients with unequivocally low cortisol levels, a morning ACTH level can help distinguish between primary and secondary adrenal insufficiency."
]
},
{
"type":"inline-wrap",
"wrapId":"1",
"contentIds":[
"mk19_bb_en_s15_inline_t1"
],
"forceOpen":true
},
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"e7dc0a",
"children":[
"For nondiagnostic cortisol values, select stimulation testing with synthetic ACTH (cosyntropin). A stimulated serum cortisol >18 μg/dL excludes adrenal insufficiency."
]
},
{
"type":"heading",
"class":"tricked",
"children":[
"Don't Be Tricked"
]
},
{
"type":"list",
"class":"tricked",
"children":[
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"70abb3",
"children":[
"Approximately 50% of patients with autoimmune adrenal insufficiency have other autoimmune endocrine disorders (thyroid disease, type 1 diabetes, vitiligo), referred to as ",
{
"type":"tag",
"tagName":"b",
"attrs":{
},
"children":[
"autoimmune polyglandular syndrome"
]
},
"; testing for these disorders is indicated."
]
},
" "
]
}
]
},
{
"type":"section",
"id":"mk19_bb_en_s15_3",
"title":{
"__html":"Treatment"
},
"titleNode":{
"type":"section-title",
"hlId":"4c4ac0",
"children":[
"Treatment"
]
},
"children":[
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"74a8dd",
"children":[
"If acute adrenal insufficiency is suspected, treat empirically with high-dose (4 mg) dexamethasone and IV saline without waiting for the ACTH and cortisol level results to return from the laboratory. ",
{
"type":"alert",
"children":[
"Dexamethasone does not interfere with the serum cortisol assay."
]
}
]
},
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"200056",
"children":[
"Chronic replacement therapy:"
]
},
{
"type":"list",
"children":[
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"a1abe5",
"children":[
"oral hydrocortisone 15 to 25 mg/d (standard dose)"
]
},
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"f4d77b",
"children":[
"oral fludrocortisone (primary adrenal insufficiency)"
]
},
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"1e516b",
"children":[
"oral hydrocortisone 2 to 10 times standard dose during periods of physiologic stress, including minor surgery"
]
},
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"2d7bb8",
"children":[
"IV hydrocortisone 100 mg followed by 50 mg every 6 h for major stress (major surgery, trauma, critical illness, childbirth)"
]
},
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"fa4379",
"children":[
"fludrocortisone is not required in primary adrenal insufficiency if the hydrocortisone dose >40 mg/d"
]
},
" "
]
},
{
"type":"heading",
"class":"tricked",
"children":[
"Don't Be Tricked"
]
},
{
"type":"list",
"class":"tricked",
"children":[
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"30a896",
"children":[
"Do not prescribe dexamethasone for chronic replacement therapy."
]
},
" "
]
}
]
},
{
"type":"section",
"id":"mk19_bb_en_s15_4",
"title":{
"__html":"Test Yourself"
},
"titleNode":{
"type":"section-title",
"hlId":"7866cc",
"children":[
"Test Yourself"
]
},
"children":[
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"287e8e",
"class":"test",
"children":[
"A 32-year-old man with hypothyroidism has a 3-month history of fatigue, weakness, nausea, and a 13.9-kg (30-lb) weight loss. He has orthostatic hypotension and increased pigment in the palmar creases. The serum sodium level is 132 mEq/L and the serum potassium level is 5 mEq/L."
]
},
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"927d75",
"class":"test_answer",
"children":[
{
"type":"tag",
"tagName":"b",
"attrs":{
},
"children":[
"Answer:"
]
},
" ",
"For diagnosis, choose autoimmune adrenalitis."
]
}
]
}
]
},
